ref: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.169, p.437 (1971)
title: Measurements of spallation cross sections for 590 MeV protons on thin targets of copper, nickel, iron and aluminum

x4freetext: Measurements of spallation cross sections for 590 MeV
protons on thin targets of copper, nickel, iron and
aluminum

x4codes.hlp: Idaho Nuclear Corp., Idaho Falls, ID, United States of America

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.169, p.437 (1971)

x4codes.hlp: Space Radiation Effects Lab., Newport News, VA, United States of America

x4freetext: For long lived products
For short lived products
the targets were irradiated in air at a distance of
4 m from a 60 deg bending magnet and of 1 m from a
thin Al window at the end of the vacuum system, thus
strongly reducing the secondary neutron flux at the
target position.
Short-lived activities (about less than 15 min half-
life) were transported by means of a rabbit system
and not normalized to the monitor reaction given.
Foils of natural Cu, Ni, Fe and Al with thicknesses
ranging from 50 to 1000 mg/cm2 and impurities ranging
from 99.90% for Fe to 99.999% for the other foils
were irradiated simultaneously.
To prevent contamination from recoil nuclei the foils
were separated by 18 mg/cm2 plastic.
The total package was thin enough that there were No
measurable effects from secondary particles.
Short-lived activities with half-lives less than about
15 min were produced in cylindrical targets of 7 mm
diameter and 15 mm length transported by a fast
rabbit system.
It is not explicitly quoted in the publication which
of the measured activities were obtained from this
kind of target.
The iron rabbits showed a higher degree of impurities
than the other rabbits and the target foils resulting
in a higher manganese concentration in the spallation
products relative to the produced scandium.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The errors given include uncertainties and
reproductivities of the gamma-ray intensities
determined.
For stronger transitions the absolute intensity was
accurate to 5%.
Included are also uncertainties of the branching
ratios and half-lives.
Not included is the error in the monitor cross section.
